-- State landlord/tenant law seed — batch (generated by genStateLawSeed.ts).
-- Sourced from official .gov statutes 2026-06-11; every value cited + independently verified
-- against the quoted statute text before seeding. Provisions attach to each state's 'residential'
-- act; a topic absent for a state = no statutory value exists (NOT invented). Hedged + dated +
-- disclaimered at surface time per the S442 posture. States: NH, ME, RI, MT, DE, SD, ND, AK, VT, WY.
--
-- SOURCING NOTES (nuances the figures alone don't capture — read before relying on a value):
-- [NH] OFFICIAL SOURCE: New Hampshire General Court statutes, formerly at gencourt.state.nh.us, now permanently redirected (301) to gc.nh.gov. All URLs use the live gc.nh.gov host.
-- [NH] ACTS / UNIT-TYPE MAPPING:
-- [NH] - Residential dwellings (apartment, single_family) are governed by the pairing of RSA 540 (Actions Against Tenants — eviction, notice to quit, grounds) and RSA 540-A (Prohibited Practices and Security Deposits). These two chapters together form the residential landlord-tenant act; NH has no single consolidated "residential tenancy act." Security-deposit rules in RSA 540-A:5-8 carry some exemptions (e.g., certain single-family owner-occupant arrangements), but the notice and prohibited-practices framework reaches all residential tenancies.
-- [NH] - mobile_home / rv_spot: RSA 205-A (Regulation of Manufactured Housing Parks) governs manufactured/mobile home parks. RSA 205-A:9 makes RSA 540 applicable where not inconsistent. RV long-term lot rental is not separately codified; where an RV is used as a manufactured-home-park-style long-term residence it would fall under 205-A by analogy, but NH statute does not name RVs explicitly — rv_spot mapping to 205-A is the closest fit, not an express statutory grant.
-- [NH] - commercial: No dedicated commercial-tenancy act. Nonresidential/"nonrestricted property" tenancies are handled under RSA 540 (e.g., 540:3 gives 7 days' / 3 months' notice rules for nonresidential), with the rest left to contract.
-- [NH] - storage: RSA 451-C (Self-Service Storage Facility Liens) governs self-storage; it is NOT a residential statute.
-- [NH] PROVISIONS DELIBERATELY OMITTED (statute does not specify a residential value — no number invented):
-- [NH] - entry_notice_hours: OMITTED. RSA 540-A:3, IV prohibits a landlord from willfully entering the tenant's premises "without prior consent, other than to make emergency repairs," but sets NO general minimum number of advance-notice hours for routine entry. The only hour-figure in the chapter (48 hours' written notice) is narrowly limited to bed-bug inspection/treatment entry, not general entry, so there is no general entry_notice_hours value to record.
-- [NH] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED for residential. NH's residential statutes (RSA 540, 540-A) do NOT cap residential late fees and impose no percentage limit. IMPORTANT TRAP AVOIDED: RSA 451-C:7 contains a "$20 or 20 percent ... whichever is greater" late-fee standard, but RSA 451-C is the SELF-SERVICE STORAGE FACILITY LIENS chapter (Title XLI), applying only to storage-unit operators — it does NOT apply to residential rent. Do not attribute that cap to residential tenancies.
-- [NH] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED for residential. No residential grace period is set in RSA 540/540-A. The 5-day grace ("late fee shall not be imposed if the renter pays ... in full by the fifth day after the due date") is again RSA 451-C:7 — storage only — not residential.
-- [NH] NOTE on notice_to_vacate: RSA 540:3, II's flat 30-day residential notice has a 7-day exception for specified for-cause grounds (RSA 540:2, II(a),(b),(d),(h) — nonpayment, substantial damage, etc.). The recorded value (30 days, min) reflects the baseline no-fault month-to-month termination notice.
