-- [ME] Sources are the official Maine Legislature statute site (legislature.maine.gov / mainelegislature.org), current through the First Special Session of the 132nd Legislature (Oct. 2025).
-- [ME] ACT SCOPE:
-- [ME] - RESIDENTIAL: General residential landlord-tenant law is split across two chapters of Title 14. Chapter 710 (Rental Property, §§6001-6030) covers tenancy-at-will termination, access/entry, late fees, habitability, evictions; Chapter 710-A (§§6031-6039) covers security deposits and is expressly limited to "residential rental units" / "a dwelling intended for human habitation." Treated here as a single residential act keyed to the §6032 "dwelling intended for human habitation" scope. Covers apartment and single_family.
-- [ME] - MOBILE_HOME_PARK: Title 10, Chapter 953 governs mobile home parks with its own parallel provisions (entry/detainer §9097-B, late-payment penalties §9097-C, security deposits §9098, habitability §9099). It is SEPARATE from the Title 14 residential act and tenants in mobile home parks are governed by Ch. 953, not Ch. 710.
-- [ME] RV / rv_spot: Maine has NO dedicated RV-park or recreational-vehicle long-term tenancy act. The Title 10 Ch. 953 definitions (§9091) define "mobile home" as a structure 8+ body feet wide, 32+ body feet long, built on a permanent chassis — which excludes recreational vehicles and travel trailers. RVs are therefore not covered by the mobile-home-park act and have no separate statute, so no act is mapped to rv_spot.
-- [ME] COMMERCIAL / storage: Maine has no dedicated commercial-tenancy statute; commercial leases are governed by general contract/common law and the eviction (forcible entry & detainer) procedures of Title 14 Ch. 709, not a substantive landlord-tenant code. Self-storage is governed by a separate lien statute (Title 10 Ch. 763, Self-Service Storage Facilities) which is not a landlord-tenant act in the residential sense. No act mapped to commercial or storage.
-- [ME] RESIDENTIAL PROVISIONS — all six requested provisions ARE specified in Maine statute and are included with verbatim evidence:
-- [ME] - deposit_return_days: §6033 sets two different deadlines — 21 days for a tenancy at will, and up to 30 days (as stated in the agreement) for a written lease. The 30-day figure (the statutory maximum for written agreements) is recorded as the ruleKind=max value; note the 21-day tenancy-at-will deadline in implementation.
-- [ME] - entry_notice_hours: §6025 does not impose an absolute hard requirement — it requires "reasonable notice" and creates a rebuttable presumption that 24 hours is reasonable. Recorded as 24 (min) on that presumption.
-- [ME] - late_fee: §6028 caps the penalty at 4% of one month's rent and provides a 15-day grace period (rent is "late" only after 15 days). Section also requires the landlord to give written notice of the penalty at lease signing.
