-- [DE] All provisions verified against the official Delaware Code at delcode.delaware.gov (Title 25). The residential act is a multi-chapter body (the "Residential Landlord-Tenant Code," 25 Del. C. ch. 51-59); § 5101 applies it to residential rental units statewide, and § 5101(b) expressly excludes commercial rental units (which fall to ch. 61 / general contract principles). § 5102 also excludes hotels/motels/transient lodging and short-term coastal rentals of 120 days or less.
-- [DE] rv_spot mapping: Delaware has NO separate RV-park statute. Chapter 70 is limited to "manufactured homes" (HUD-code/mobile homes) and manufactured-home community lots; an RV is not a manufactured home under the Act, so a long-term RV lot rental defaults to the Residential Landlord-Tenant Code (ch. 51-59). I mapped rv_spot under the residential act for that reason; if GAM wants RV spots treated as park-model/manufactured-home lots in a given community, ch. 70 could apply instead.
-- [DE] Chapter 70 (manufactured homes) has its own deposit, rent-increase (CPI-U capped, once per 12 months), and termination rules that differ from the residential figures above; in the absence of a ch. 70 provision, the Residential Landlord-Tenant Code governs (25 Del. C. § 7003).
-- [DE] Deposit note: the 1-month cap (§ 5514(a)(2)) applies to leases of 1 year or more; for month-to-month tenancies the statute does not impose the same 1-month ceiling, and pet deposits up to 1 month and furnished-unit surcharges are separately allowed under § 5514. The 20-day return clock and double-damages penalty for wrongful withholding apply across the board.
-- [DE] Late fee note: § 5501(d) also extends the rent due date by 3 days if the landlord fails to maintain a payment office in the county where the unit is located — relevant to when the 5-day grace begins.
--
-- [SD] South Dakota does NOT have separate mobile-home-park or RV-park acts. All real-property leases fall under SDCL ch. 43-32 (Lease of Real Property): single-family/apartments are the core residential coverage; mobile/manufactured homes are addressed within it (43-32-31 governs 90-day notice to vacate/remove a mobile or manufactured home); RV park long-term stays are addressed by 43-32-37 (ejection from hotel/campground/RV park premises); commercial leases are covered too (43-32-24.1 commercial security deposits). Self-storage is the only separate regime, under SDCL ch. 44-14 (Self-Service Storage Facilities Liens), which is a lien statute, not a tenancy act.
-- [SD] OMITTED provisions (no statute exists — not invented): (1) late_fee_max_pct — South Dakota imposes no statutory cap on late fees; ch. 43-32 (sections 43-32-1 through 43-32-37) contains no late-fee section. (2) late_fee_grace_days — no mandatory grace period exists in statute; rent is late on the date the lease specifies unless the lease grants a grace period.
-- [SD] deposit_return_days CAUTION / version transition: SDCL 43-32-24 has two versions. The version EFFECTIVE THROUGH June 30, 2026 requires return 'within two weeks' (14 days): 'Every lessor of residential premises shall, within two weeks after the termination of the tenancy and receipt of the tenant's mailing address or delivery instructions, return the security deposit ...'. The amended version EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026 changes this to twenty-one days. I seeded 21 days because it is the durable forward-looking value as of the database build, but if the reference DB must reflect law in force exactly on today's date (2026-06-11), the in-force value is 14 days until 2026-06-30. Both versions also require, on request, an itemized accounting within 45 days, forfeiture of withholding rights for noncompliance, and punitive damages up to $200 for bad-faith retention.
-- [SD] notice_to_vacate_days basis: 43-32-15 caps the required termination notice at 'not exceeding one month'; for a month-to-month tenancy the term is one month, yielding ~30 days. 43-32-13 separately uses thirty-day language for landlord modification of month-to-month terms (and gives the tenant 15 days after a modification notice to terminate effective the first of the next month). The 30-day month-to-month termination figure is well-supported but is derived from the 'one month' statutory term rather than an explicit numeric '30 days' in the general-termination section.
--
-- [ND] All residential values verified verbatim from the official North Dakota Legislative Branch PDF (ndlegis.gov) for NDCC ch. 47-16; the chapter PDF was downloaded and text-extracted to confirm exact wording.
-- [ND] OMITTED provisions (statute does NOT specify a value — not invented):
-- [ND] - entry_notice_hours: NDCC § 47-16-07.3 ("When landlord may enter apartment") sets NO fixed advance-notice hours/days. It permits entry "only during reasonable hours, and in a reasonable manner" and requires that "[u]nless it is impractical to do so the landlord shall first notify and receive the consent of the tenant... which consent shall identify a time certain." No numeric notice period exists, so omitted.
-- [ND] - late_fee_max_pct and late_fee_grace_days: Chapter 47-16 contains NO late-fee provision whatsoever (grep of the full official chapter text returned zero matches for late fee/charge/grace). North Dakota does not cap residential late fees or mandate a grace period by statute. Both omitted.
-- [ND] - deposit_max_months note: base cap is 1 month's rent. § 47-16-07.1(1)(a)-(b) allows up to 2 months only for tenants convicted of a felony or with a prior judgment for violating a rental agreement; a separate pet deposit (not a general security deposit) may be the greater of $2,500 or 2 months' rent under § 47-16-07.1(2). The min/max model captures the general residential ceiling of 1 month.
-- [ND] ACTS / coverage notes:
-- [ND] - North Dakota has NO standalone Uniform Residential Landlord & Tenant Act and NO dedicated mobile-home-park or RV-park tenancy act. The general 'Leasing of Real Property' chapter (NDCC ch. 47-16) governs apartments, single-family dwellings, and — by default — mobile-home lot rentals and RV long-term tenancies. It is a general real-property leasing chapter (also contains farm-lease and oil/gas-lease sections), so commercial leases also fall under it absent a separate commercial statute.
-- [ND] - Mobile home parks get ONE supplemental statute: NDCC § 47-10-28 (located in ch. 47-10 'Real Property Transfers'), which adds mobile-home-park-specific tenant protections — notably a 90-day notice requirement before any rent increase on month-to-month mobile-home-park tenancies ('Any month-to-month tenancy agreement must provide a minimum of ninety days' notice to the tenant before any rent increase is effective'), ownership-transfer disclosure within 5 business days, and a 6-month rent-freeze on new owners in certain cases. This is NOT a full tenancy code; mobile-home park tenancies still rely on ch. 47-16 for deposits, return, entry, and termination. Verified verbatim from ndlegis.gov ch. 47-10 PDF.
-- [ND] - Storage: self-service storage rentals are governed by the lien framework in NDCC ch. 35-33 (Title 35 Liens), not by 47-16. (ND also has ch. 35-36 'Portable Storage Unit Property Lien' for portable units.) These are lien/enforcement statutes, not landlord-tenant deposit/entry statutes, so no 47-16-style provisions apply.
-- [ND] - rv_spot was mapped to the residential act (ch. 47-16) because ND has no RV-park-specific tenancy statute; long-term RV lot rentals default to the general leasing chapter.
--
-- [AK] Source: Alaska State Legislature official statutes (akleg.gov), Alaska Statutes 2024. Verified verbatim from the statute print interface.
-- [AK] ACT COVERAGE: Alaska has ONE residential act, the Uniform Residential Landlord and Tenant Act (AS 34.03, short title confirmed at AS 34.03.380). It governs all residential dwelling units. "Dwelling unit" is defined broadly at AS 34.03.360(3) as "a structure or a part of a structure that is used as a home, residence, or sleeping place," which covers apartments, single-family houses, mobile homes, and RVs used as long-term residences. Transient occupancy in a hotel/motel/lodging is excluded (AS 34.03.330(b)(4)).
-- [AK] MOBILE HOME / RV: There is NO separate mobile-home-park or RV-park act in Alaska. Mobile home park tenancies are governed by URLTA itself, with ADDITIONAL eviction/notice protections embedded at AS 34.03.225 (e.g., a mobile home park operator may evict only for enumerated reasons; a change in land use requires at least 270 days' notice). RV long-term tenants used as a residence fall under URLTA via the general "dwelling unit" definition; rv_spot is mapped to the residential act accordingly.
-- [AK] COMMERCIAL: Alaska has no dedicated commercial landlord-tenant statute. URLTA applies only to residential dwelling units; commercial leases are governed by the lease contract and common law. No commercial act returned in the structured acts list.
-- [AK] STORAGE: Self-storage is covered by the Self-Storage Facility Liens statute (AS 34.35.600 - 34.35.695), a lien-enforcement statute rather than a full tenancy act. Note: this storage statute contains a late-fee provision (reasonable if not exceeding the greater of $20 or 20% of monthly rent) but that applies ONLY to self-storage, NOT to residential tenancies.
-- [AK] OMITTED RESIDENTIAL PROVISIONS (statute does NOT specify - not invented):
-- [AK] - late_fee_max_pct: OMITTED. URLTA imposes no cap on residential late fees. AS 34.03.020 leaves rent and fee terms to the parties' agreement ("The landlord and tenant may include in a rental agreement clauses and conditions not prohibited by this chapter or by law, including rent, terms of agreement"). No statutory percentage cap exists in AS 34.03.
-- [AK] - late_fee_grace_days: OMITTED. No statutory grace period before a residential late fee may apply. Rent is "payable without demand or notice at the time and place agreed upon" (AS 34.03.020(c)); no grace period is mandated by the act.
-- [AK] DEPOSIT RETURN NUANCE: AS 34.03.070(g) sets 14 days as the default return deadline; this extends to 30 days if the landlord deducts for damages under AS 34.03.120. The minimum/default statutory deadline (14 days) is reported as deposit_return_days.
