-- [VT] Source: official Vermont Legislature statutes site (legislature.vermont.gov). All values verified against actual statutory text.
-- [VT] ACTS:
-- [VT] - Residential act = 9 V.S.A. Chapter 137 "Residential Rental Agreements." Governs apartments and standard residential dwellings (single_family). § 4451 ties obligations to "residential rental agreements" / "dwelling units."
-- [VT] - Mobile home parks = 10 V.S.A. Chapter 153, a SEPARATE statute governing lot rentals in mobile home parks (mobile_home unit type).
-- [VT] - RV / rv_spot: NO separate Vermont act, and explicitly EXCLUDED from the mobile-home-park chapter by 10 V.S.A. § 6204: "This chapter shall not apply to the rental or use of campsites occupied for vacation or recreational purposes by camping units, such as: tents, yurts, tepees, lean-tos, camping cabins, and recreational vehicles, including motor homes, folding camping trailers, conventional travel trailers, fifth wheel travel trailers, truck campers, van campers, and conversion vehicles..." Long-term RV/campsite occupancy in VT is not covered by either the residential or mobile-home statutes (common-law / contract). rv_spot intentionally NOT mapped to any act.
-- [VT] - commercial and storage: NO Vermont statutory landlord-tenant act. Chapter 137 is residential-only; commercial leases and self-storage are governed by common law / contract (and any separate lien statutes), not a tenancy act. No act returned for these unit types.
-- [VT] PROVISIONS (residential, Chapter 137):
-- [VT] - entry_notice_hours = 48h min (§ 4460(b)), entry permitted 9:00 A.M.–9:00 P.M.
-- [VT] - deposit_return_days = 14 days standard (§ 4461(a)). Note: a separate 60-day window applies to seasonal/non-primary-residence rentals; the 14-day general rule is recorded as the residential default.
-- [VT] - notice_to_vacate_days = 60 days min (§ 4467(c)(1)(A)) for tenancies of two years or less; rises to 90 days for tenancies over two years (§ 4467(c)(1)(B)). Recorded the 60-day floor.
-- [VT] OMITTED (statute does not specify — not invented):
-- [VT] - deposit_max_months: Vermont Chapter 137 has NO cap on security deposit amount. OMITTED.
-- [VT] - late_fee_max_pct and late_fee_grace_days: Chapter 137 contains NO late-fee provisions — no max percentage, no dollar cap, no grace period. Confirmed absent in full-chapter review. Both OMITTED.
--
-- [WY] SOURCE: All statutory text verified directly from the official Wyoming Legislature site (wyoleg.gov), Title 1, Chapter 21, Article 12 (Residential Rental Property Act).
-- [WY] ACT SCOPE: Wyoming has only ONE substantive landlord-tenant act — the Residential Rental Property Act (Wyo. Stat. §§ 1-21-1201 to 1-21-1211). It is a minimal-regulation statute. Per the § 1-21-1201 definition of "residential rental unit," it covers a renter's principal place of residence (apartments, single-family dwellings) but EXPRESSLY EXCLUDES "a mobile home lot or recreational property rented on an occasional basis." Exact language: '"Residential rental unit" means a renter's principal place of residence and includes the appurtenances, grounds, common areas and facilities... excluding a mobile home lot or recreational property rented on an occasional basis.'
-- [WY] NO SEPARATE MOBILE HOME PARK ACT or RV PARK ACT exists in Wyoming. Mobile home lots, RV spaces, commercial, and storage rentals fall to general contract/common law for substantive terms; the only statutory framework touching them is the Forcible Entry and Detainer eviction procedure (Title 1, Ch. 21, Art. 10, §§ 1-21-1001 et seq.), which is procedural (notice to quit / eviction), not a substantive landlord-tenant rights act. Title 31, Ch. 2, Art. 5 covers mobile-home TITLING only, not park tenancy rights. The "eviction_fed" act entry is included to map those unit types to the only applicable Wyoming statute; it is procedural and was NOT mined for the residential provisions below.
-- [WY] PROVISIONS DELIBERATELY OMITTED (no statutory value exists — not invented):
-- [WY] - entry_notice_hours: NO STATUTE. The Residential Rental Property Act contains no landlord-entry notice provision. Practice requires only "reasonable" notice; no hours are fixed by statute.
-- [WY] - deposit_max_months: NO STATUTE. Wyoming sets no maximum security deposit. § 1-21-1207 only requires written notice of any NON-refundable portion; it does not cap the amount.
-- [WY] - late_fee_max_pct: NO STATUTE. The act is silent on late fees; no percentage cap.
-- [WY] - late_fee_grace_days: NO STATUTE. No mandatory grace period.
-- [WY] - notice_to_vacate_days: NO STATUTE. Wyoming has no statute setting a month-to-month termination notice period. The commonly-cited "30 days" is a common-law/customary default that the lease may modify; it is expressly NOT statutory. (§ 1-21-1003's 3-day notice to quit is an eviction-for-cause procedure, not a no-cause month-to-month termination period, so it does not map to notice_to_vacate_days.) Omitted per the no-invention rule.
-- [WY] The ONLY quantified provision in the residential act is the 30-day deposit-return deadline (§ 1-21-1208), with a statutory 30-day extension where there is damage to the unit ("If there is damage to the residential rental unit, this period shall be extended by thirty (30) days.").
